To this ‘Quelle’ I am disposed to assign the interesting passage in which we are told that the great orators oi the Republic de livered uo speeches before the centumviral court, Pollio's celebrated speeches for the heirs oi Urbinia constituting only an apparent exception. See note to c. 37 14.

The other passage which, in my judgment, was taken from the ‘Acta’ is the close of c. 34, which gives the age at which Crassus, Caesar, Asinius Pollio and Calvus made their oratorioal debut, and the names oi the men whom they prosecuted on that occasion.
